{"id":"1312.3487","submitter":"Pablo Saldanha","authors":"Pablo L. Saldanha","title":"Quantum analysis of the direct measurement of light waves","comments":"12 pages (one-column format), 2 figures. To appear in New Journal of\n  Physics","journal-ref":"New J. Phys. 16, 013021 (2014)","doi":"10.1088/1367-2630/16/1/013021","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In a beautiful experiment performed about a decade ago, Goulielmakis et al.\nmade a direct measurement of the electric field of light waves [E. Goulielmakis\net al., Science 305, 1267-1269 (2004)]. However, they used a laser source to\nproduce the light field, whose quantum state has a null expectation value for\nthe electric field operator, so how was it possible to measure this electric\nfield? Here we present a quantum treatment for the f:2f interferometer used to\ncalibrate the carrier-envelope phase of the light pulses in the experiment. We\nshow how the special nonlinear features of the f:2f interferometer can change\nthe quantum state of the electromagnetic field inside the laser cavity to a\nstate with a definite oscillating electric field, explaining how the\n\"classical\" electromagnetic field emerges in the experiment. We discuss that\nthis experiment was, to our knowledge, the first demonstration of an absolute\ncoherent superposition of different photon number states in the optical regime.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 12 Dec 2013 13:52:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-01-22"}
